[ProMED thanks Mahmoud Orabi for submitting this report.

This tick is unlike temperate zone forest ticks in that it is larger and can pursue its hosts over distances of several meters. This tick can be transported on migratory passerine birds and that may be the way it came to Norway. Apparently, just a single tick was found on the horse. As the above report mentions, it is unlikely that this tick species has become established in Norway. This tick has become established in southern Europe and carried Crimean Congo hemorrhagic fever virus (CCHFV) there. Continued surveillance in Norway and testing of any of these ticks for CCHFV would be prudent. - Mod.TY

